definition.value: Lysergol esterified with cyclohexanecarboxylic acid.

An alkaloid of the ergoline family that occurs as a minor constituent in some species of fungi and in the morning glory family of plants. Its structure is that of ergoline with a methyl group at N-6 and a beta-hydroxymethyl substituent at C-8.
One of a class of naturally occurring alkaloids with a structure based on that of ergoline.
The cyclic tetrapyrrole anion that is ferroheme o protonated to pH 7.3.
Flavin protonated to pH 7.3
Ferriheme a protonated to pH 7.3.
A gamma-poly(glutamic acid) polymer, composed of gamma-poly(L-glutamic acid) macromolecules.
A gamma-poly(glutamic acid) polymer, composed of gamma-poly(D-glutamic acid) macromolecules.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is molybdopterin guanine dinucleotide protonated to pH 7.3.
Molybdopterin cytosine dinucleotide protonated to pH 7.3
An organophosphate oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of oxotungsten-bis(molybdopterin guanine dinucleotide); major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the two diphosphate OH groups of Mo(V)-molybdopterin cytosine dinucleotide; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of molybdate-bis(molybdopterin guanine dinucleotide); major species at pH 7.3.
The penta-anion resulting from the removal of a proton from each of the carboxylic acid groups of coenzyme F430. The major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of benzylpenicillenic acid.
Degradation product of benzylpenicillin in which the thiolamino acid penicillamine and carbon dioxide from the labile carboxyl group have been lost, leaving a phenylacetylamino-acetaldehyde.
The conjugate base of m-azobenzenesulfonic acid.
Azobenzene derivative carrying a single sulfonate substituent at the meta-position.
The aroyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of 4-nitrobenzoic acid.

A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the meta positions with a glycinocarbonyl and a (racemic) leucinocarbonyl group. It is found as part of a protein conjugate in anti-GIL rabbit serum.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the meta position with a (racemic) leucinocarbonyl group.
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion arising from deprotonation of the four carboxy groups of ferroheme d1; major species at pH 7.3.
A polymer composed of poly(ether) macromolecules.
A polyether homopolymer, composed of poly(galactose) macromolecules.
A homopolymer, composed of polyacetylene macromolecules.
A polyacetylene polymer, composed of poly(ethene-1,2-diyl) macromolecules.
A polyacetylene polymer, composed of poly(diacetylene) macromolecules.
A poly(diacetylene) polymer, composed of poly(diiododiacetylene) macromolecules.
A polyacetylene polymer, composed of poly(2,5-furylene vinylene) macromolecules.

An amino trisaccharide consisting of a 3-deoxy-D-manno-oct-2-ulose residue and two glucosamine residues (one at the reducing end) in a linear sequence, with three phosphate groups attached. Isolated from the lipopolysaccharide obtained from Haemophilus influenzae.

An amino trisaccharide consisting of a 3-deoxy-D-manno-oct-2-ulose residue and two glucosamine residues (one at the reducing end) in a linear sequence, with three phosphate groups attached. Isolated from the lipopolysaccharide obtained from Haemophilus influenzae.
The radical group formally derived from benzylpenicillenate by homolysis of the S-H bond and loss of the hydrogen radical thereby formed.
A branched amino hexasaccharide corresponding to part of the lipooligosaccharide from Neisseria meningitidis.
A ferroheme coordination complex bearing 1-sulfanylethyl substituents at the 8- and 13-positions.

A glycosylglucose where the glycosyl component is D-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptopyranose attached via an alpha-(1->6)-linkage; the epitope of the lipooligosaccharide isolated from Haemophilus ducreyi strain ITM 2665.

A synthetic nonapeptide comprising cysteinyl, phenylalanyl, phenylalanyl, glutaminyl, asparaginyl, cysteinyl, prolyl, lysyl, and glycinamide residues in sequence, with a disulfide bridge joining the two cysteine residues. Its antidiuretic effects are less than those of vasopressin. It is used as a vasoconstrictor in local anaesthetic injections for dental use, and is an ingredient of preparations that have been used for treatment of pain and inflammation of the mouth.

An amino tetrasaccharide consisting of two 3-deoxy-D-manno-oct-2-ulose residues and two glucosamine residues (one at the reducing end) in a linear sequence, with a phosphate group at the reducing end. Corresponds to the core oligosaccahride isolated from Salmonella minnesota strain R 595.
The conjugate base of fenoprofen.
An azobenzene derivative carrying two para-trimethylammonium substituents.
A 3-sn-phosphatidyl L-serine in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups are both oleoyl.
An amino disaccharide consisting of a 3-deoxy-4-O-phosphono-D-manno-oct-2-ulose residue attached to beta-glucosamine via an alpha-(2->6)-linkage.
An amino disaccharide consisting of a 3-deoxy-5-O-phosphono-D-manno-oct-2-ulose residue attached to beta-glucosamine via an alpha-(2->6)-linkage.
An amino disaccharide consisting of a 3-deoxy-4-O-phosphono-D-manno-oct-2-ulose residue attached to beta-glucosamine via an alpha-(2->6)-linkage with an O-allyl group at the anomeric centre.
An amino disaccharide consisting of a 3-deoxy-5-O-phosphono-D-manno-oct-2-ulose residue attached to beta-glucosamine via an alpha-(2->6)-linkage with an O-allyl group at the anomeric centre.
The 1-O-allyl-5-phospho derivative of 3-deoxy-alpha-D-manno-oct-2-ulopyranosonic acid.
The 1-O-allyl-4-phospho derivative of 3-deoxy-alpha-D-manno-oct-2-ulopyranosonic acid.
Any member of the class of herbicides whose members contain a phenoxy or substituted phenoxy group.
